Car Prices


car1 <- CarPrices |> 
  filter(Cylinder %in% c(8, 6)) |> 
  filter(Make %in% c("Cadillac")) |> 
  mutate(Cylinder = as.factor(Cylinder))

Intro/Background

The data set CarPrices contains 804 entries that have information about different car makes and models. For this analysis we will focus on the make Cadillac including all its car models. The responsive quantitative variable will be Price, and the explanatory variables that will be use for this analysis are Mileage (quantitative) and Cylinder that contains only cars with 6 and 8 Cylinders (qualitative), and finally how they interact with each other. This analysis attempts to see if Cadillacs with 6 or 8 cylinders are more expensive when brand new and how is the vehicle depreciation over time. This data set contains 20 6 cylinder vehicle entries and 60 8 cylinder vehicle entries.

datatable(car1)

Regression Equation

A multiple linear regression model was applied to the data to obtain two regression lines, one for each type of car with 8 & 6 cylinders. The model is given by:

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Price} {=} \overbrace{\beta_0}^{\stackrel{\text{y-int}}{\text{baseline}}} + \overbrace{\beta_1}^{\stackrel{\text{slope}}{\text{baseline}}} \underbrace{X_{1i}}_\text{Mileage} + \overbrace{\beta_2}^{\stackrel{\text{change in}}{\text{y-int}}} \underbrace{X_{2i}}_\text{Cylinder} + \overbrace{\beta_3}^{\stackrel{\text{change in}}{\text{slope}}} \underbrace{X_{1i}X_{2i}}_\text{Mileage:Cylinders} + \epsilon_i \] where \(\epsilon_i\sim N(0,\sigma^2)\) and \(X_{i2} = 0\) for 6 cylinder vehicles and \(X_{i2} = 1\) 8 cylinder vehicles. This forced 0, 1 encoding for \(X_{i2}\) produces the following models.

Cylinders Value of \(X_{i2}\) Resulting Model
6 \(X_{i2} = 0\) \(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)
8 \(X_{i2} = 1\) \(Y_i = (\beta_0 + \beta_2) + (\beta_1 + \beta_3) X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)

The two separated model show that β2 = the difference between y-intercepts for the 8 and 6 cylinder Cadillac vehicles β3 = the difference in the slopes for the two models

For analysis we assume that the y-intercept of both models is greater than zero, and that the Cadillac vehicles with 8 and 6 cylinders depreciate over time, so we don’t need to test the coefficients of β0 or β1 to find differences from zero. Another assumptions is that the baseline intercept and slope for the 6 cylinders vehicles are also different from zero. What will be tested in this analysis is the whether the regression lines for cars with 8 and 6 cylinders have different y-intercept and slope, so we will test β2 and β3 for differences from zero.

\[\text{These hypotheses will be judged at the following significance level}\] \[ \alpha = 0.05 \]

\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \\ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \]

Test for Equal y-Intercepts

If β2 is zero in the combined regression model, then y-intercept (representing the average cost of brand new cars) would be the same for 8 and 6 cylinders. But if β2 is greater than zero, then cars with 8 cylinders cost more than 6 cylinder Cadillac cars on average. In the same ways if β2 is less than zero, that means that 8 cylinder cars cost less.

\[ H_0: \beta_2 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal average cost when brand new)} \\ H_a: \beta_2 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal average cost when brand new)} \]

Test for Equal slopes

For this set of hypotheses if β3 is zero in the combined regression model, that means that the slopes of both lines have no difference (they are the same). That would suggest that the value loss for both 8 and 6 cylinder Cadillac cars is the same for both car types. If β3 is not equal to zero, that means that one of the car types (8 or 6 cylinders) depreciates faster than the other.

\[ H_0: \beta_3 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal rates of depreciation)} \\ H_a: \beta_3 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal rates of depreciation)} \]

Graphical Summary

This scartterplot shows the of Price and Mileage for Cadillacs that had 8 and 6 cylinders, and the regression summary is below the plot. It shows that vehicles with 8 Cylinders cost $12,799 more than Cadillacs with 6 Cylinders when it’s brand new (p-value = 0.02587). In the same way, Cadillacs with 6 cylinders depreciate slower than the ones with 8 cylinders, it is because vehicles with 8 cylinders lose in value $0.36 for each mile which represents $0.16 more depreciation than vehicles with 6 cylinders that only lose $0.22 per driven mile.

palette(c("skyblue","firebrick"))

plot(Price ~ Mileage, data=car1, col= Cylinder, main="Price and Milage Comparison for Cars with 8 and 6 Cylinders", pch=16)

car.lm <- lm(Price ~  Mileage + Cylinder + Mileage:Cylinder, data=car1)

c <- coef(car.lm)
abline(c[1], c[2], col=palette()[1])

abline(c[1]+c[3], c[2]+c[4], col=palette()[2])

text(1300,37895, "$37,895", cex=0.6, col="gray55", pos=3, offset=.25)
  points(0,37895, pch=16, col="gray55", cex=0.5)
  
text(1300,50694, "$50,694", cex=0.6, col="gray55", pos=3, offset=.25)
  points(0,50694, pch=16, col="gray55", cex=0.5)

legend("topright", legend=c("6 Cylinders","8 Cylinders"), pch=1, col=palette(), title="Cadillac Cylinders", bty="n")

Multiple Linear Regression Model Analysis

car.lm <- lm(Price ~  Mileage + Cylinder + Mileage:Cylinder, data=car1)
pander(car.lm, caption="Regression Summary for Price Output on Mileage According to Cylinder Type")
Regression Summary for Price Output on Mileage According to Cylinder Type
  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 37895 4998 7.582 6.925e-11
Mileage -0.2247 0.2598 -0.8649 0.3898
Cylinder8 12799 5632 2.273 0.02587
Mileage:Cylinder8 -0.1595 0.2866 -0.5566 0.5794

β0 is represented by the Intercept as the coefficient estimate

β1 is represented by Mileage as the coefficient estimate

β2 is represented by Cylinder8 as the coefficient estimate

β3 is represented by Mileage:Cylinder8 as the coefficient estimate

Cylinder8 is the difference between the two y-intercepts

Mileage:Cylinder8 is the difference between the two slopes

Requirements with the Regression

The residual vs fitted graph shows that the data is not linear because the red line isn’t flat, so it doesn’t show normal line. In term of normal variance, we cannot assume this data to be have constant variance because of the lack of vertical variability of the dots doesn’t seem to look normal across the fitted values. The graph shows three different outliers (observation 72, 73, and 75) that can disproportionately influence the regression. These three observation can be remove form the data set to see if the results of the regression are affected in some way by them. The lack of normality toward the upper right corner of the residual that is visible in the Q-Q plot of the residual can be considered as a violation. There is no pattern in the residual vs order plot, so we can not assume a normal distribution for this data set.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(car.lm, which=1)
qqPlot(car.lm$residuals)
## [1] 73 75
mtext(side=3,text="Q-Q Plot of Residuals")
plot(car.lm$residuals, type="b")
mtext(side=3, text="Residuals vs. Order")

Simple Linear Regression

Even though the third term was dropped in order to conduct a simple linear regression to make a comparison, the same data set was used for this final part of the analysis. We can see how the data is exactly distributed and scattered in the plot with the only difference that there is no second line to compare 8 and 6 cylinder Cadillacs, and that the line is some how between the two lines shown in the multiple linear regression graph, but somehow getting closer to the upper line because it’s taking the data as a whole and not grouping it by the two different cylinder car types.

Slope and Y-intercept

The slopes and y-intercept can be placed as an “in between” range between the two slopes and y-intercepts of the multiple linear regression that were shown before.

Regression Equation for Mileage or 1st intercept \[ \hat{Y}_i = \overbrace{40217}^{\stackrel{\text{y-int Mileage}}{\text{}}} - \overbrace{0.3557}^{\stackrel{\text{slope}}{\text{}}} X_{1i} \] Regression Equation for Cylinder or 2nd intercept

\[ \hat{Y}_i = \overbrace{50145}^{\stackrel{\text{y-int Cylinder}}{\text{}}} - \overbrace{0.3557}^{\stackrel{\text{slope}}{\text{}}} X_{1i} \]

Regression Model Analysis

Both the slope and y-intercept of this linear regression model seem not to be placed in the middle between the two slopes and y-intercepts of the multiple linear regression model, but they are a little higher than that. So we can say that a linear regression model for this analysis does not provide the average calculations between the the different results for the slope and y-intercept of the multiple linear regression, but rather the results of the linear regression seem to begetting closer to the high end on the multiple linear one.

Check the Requirements with the Regression

First of all, we can see that the red line of the residuals vs fitted plot look more convex than the one for the multiple linear analysis, the inconsistencies of the observations changed a little bit because in this case the outliers are 71, 72, and 73 but for the multiple linear were 71, 72, and 75. The Q-Q plot of the residual look a little different for this analysis compared to the multiple one, in this case the outliers change from 73 and 75 to 71 and 73, and the vertical consistency of the observation seems a little more aggressive going up and down, so the lack of normality in this case is more visible. Finally, the residual vs order shows a pattern with more groups going up and down than the on for the multiple linear regression.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(car.lm2, which=1)

Conclusion/Future Studies

Basically, if a Cadillac with 6 cylinder was bought at a price of $37,895 and an 8 cylinder one for $50,694. We will assume that each car was driven for 30,000 miles and sold for their average price at 30,000 miles of $31,154 for a 6 cylinder car, and $39,168 for an 8 cylinder one. This would result in a loss of $6,741 for a 6 cylinder Cadillac and a loss of $11,526 for a 8 cylinder Cadillac. Over 30,000 miles of use, owning a 6 cylinder Cadillac will save the owner $4,785 over a 8 cylinder one. The numbers used for this conclusion were taken form the regression model analysis summary of the multiple linear regression model.

This data was collected from KSL and belong to a single day, for future studies more data can be collected to show the variance and change over time in order to conduct an analysis with more information to predict with more accuracy the desire outcome or purpose of the study based on hsitorical data than has mor infoormaiton thatn just one single day.
